</p>
<note number="2">Quantity can be specified using amount, duration etc.</note>
</ext_description>
<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Required_resource_arm  Entity: Required_resource_assignment  
   <express_ref linkend="required_resource:arm:Required_resource_arm.Required_resource_assignment"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Required_resource_arm.Required_resource_assignment">
<p>A Required_resource_assignment is an association of a resource requirement statement with one or
more entities that requires the resource. 
The resource requirement statement could be related to many different types of entities such as:
task, task step, activity, activity method, organization etc.
</p>
<p>The role of the assignment is determined by classification.</p>
<note number="1">
The assignment can be classified as "Required_by", etc.
</note>
<note number="2">
An association between a required resource and actions that are needed prior to its usage, is established
using the required_resource_action_item or required_resource_task_item in the 
  <module_ref linkend="Required_resource_characterized:1_scope"> Required resource characterized
  </module_ref> module.
</note>
<example number="1">A resource required by the activity "12" needs to be calibrated prior to usage. 
The calibration activity "21" is associated with the same required resource using the required_resource_activity_item
in the <module_ref linkend="Required_resource_characterized:1_scope"> Required resource characterized
  </module_ref> module.</example>
<example number="2">A resource required by the task "123" needs to be disposed after its usage. 
This disposal task "456" is associated with the same required resource using required_resource_task_item
in the <module_ref linkend="Required_resource_characterized:1_scope"> Required resource characterized
  </module_ref> module.</example>
</ext_description>
